Not sure, if I understood you correctly - if you want function `ab` to be scoped to either `A` or `B`, then your generic type parameter should reflect this requirement as well. You&#39;ll want to change you code to:

```
// given A, restrict item to &#39;1&#39; | &#39;2&#39; | &#39;3&#39;
ab&lt;A&gt;(&quot;a&quot;, &quot;1&quot;); // ok
ab&lt;A&gt;(&quot;a&quot;, &quot;4&quot;); // error (ok)

// given A, restrict item to &#39;4&#39; | &#39;5&#39; | &#39;6&#39;
ab&lt;B&gt;(&quot;b&quot;, &quot;4&quot;); // ok
ab&lt;B&gt;(&quot;b&quot;, &quot;1&quot;); // error (ok)
```
[Playground][1]

Above code has the slight disadvantage, that the generic type parameter has to be set manually. If one day `U = TypeProperty&lt;T, &#39;label&#39;&gt;` cannot provide a default type anymore, `U` has to be added as well in every code place involving `ab` and cannot be inferred.

An alternative is to create a [lookup type][2] `LabelToList`. This style is advantageous, if you only have a couple interfaces like `A` and `B` and many `ab` invocations. You can omit the manual generic type parameters by coding your example like this:
```
type LabelToList = {
  a: A;
  b: B;
};

function ab&lt;K extends keyof LabelToList&gt;(
  label: K,
  item: LabelToList[K][&quot;list&quot;]
) {}
```
